1
00:00:03,608 --> 00:00:29,785
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhu Dasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhu Dasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhu Dasa

2
00:00:33,426 --> 00:00:37,378
Homage to the fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:37,518 --> 00:00:40,948
Excuse me, I forgot.

4
00:00:40,969 --> 00:00:42,131
It's including the chant.

5
00:00:44,218 --> 00:00:47,588
Just see if I just want me to answer these, just a minute.

6
00:01:04,477 --> 00:01:11,325
I've observed that laziness or sloth and torpor is a state closely related to one's intentions.

7
00:01:12,147 --> 00:01:14,650
The road to hell is paved with good intentions.

8
00:01:21,400 --> 00:01:27,046
There's a distinction between sloth and torpor and laziness to be made, right?

9
00:01:27,066 --> 00:01:27,548
It's on the earth.

10
00:01:28,355 --> 00:01:56,944
vocabulary distinction sloth and torpor are products of past laziness laziness as I see it is where you make a decision not to put energy into something being lazy that could come from just not caring or just because you're fed up or whatever but laziness is more to do with an attitude rather than when we're talking about defilement sloth and torpor

11
00:01:57,262 --> 00:02:00,465
They're referring to the consequences of laziness.

12
00:02:00,646 --> 00:02:04,230
So that heaviness in the head and the heaviness in the body and all that.

13
00:02:05,371 --> 00:02:08,616
So when it comes to laziness it's definitely to do with your intentions.

14
00:02:11,019 --> 00:02:15,985
Don't be lazy.

15
00:02:16,064 --> 00:02:18,647
Could you please say a little about developing equanimity?

16
00:02:19,650 --> 00:02:26,457
I find I can't let go and not not

17
00:02:27,687 --> 00:02:28,527
react to things.

18
00:02:29,308 --> 00:02:43,429
Equanimity comes with an attitude from a position of not knowing, not wanting to engage.

19
00:02:45,070 --> 00:02:50,538
So when something comes up and you find yourself

20
00:02:51,110 --> 00:03:20,121
unable not to be drawn into it see try and try and sort of sit back within yourself to see that resistance or the desire to engage it's one of the two it's either a desire to indulge or a desire to push away and just try to get in contact with that as soon as that becomes an object to you and it's it's more like an energy more like an energy than a feat than an emotion or anything more like a

21
00:03:20,336 --> 00:03:26,044
And as long as you can keep that there, you see, you must have moved back into an equanimous position.

22
00:03:26,225 --> 00:03:27,227
It arises naturally.

23
00:03:28,087 --> 00:03:30,632
You don't have to worry too much about equanimity as such.

24
00:03:31,092 --> 00:03:44,932
What you have to be concerned about is being able to make that compulsive wanting, that compulsive indulgence, or compulsive rejection, the object.

25
00:03:46,655 --> 00:03:48,758
You've got to come back on yourself, you see.

26
00:04:01,258 --> 00:04:28,887
a couple of times I've said the body becomes extremely heavy while the mind remains completely wide and awake can you say something about this it's sometimes like that laughter laughter laughter

27
00:04:30,502 --> 00:04:33,307
These conditions just arise, that's it.

28
00:04:33,326 --> 00:04:40,596
So sometimes the body, that heaviness is in the body, which means that the mental state is in the body.

29
00:04:42,759 --> 00:04:44,302
And yet you're bright and awake.

30
00:04:44,682 --> 00:04:58,079
Now, you may find that even in the head, when you feel really dull, and it's like porridge in there, and you can feel yourself constantly falling into that sleepiness, and you don't feel you're awake within it.

31
00:04:58,651 --> 00:05:06,660
If you really make the effort to keep moving around and feeling it and feeling it and experiencing it, you'd be surprised.

32
00:05:06,680 --> 00:05:09,262
You'd wake up like a light bulb in the midst of that fog.

33
00:05:10,684 --> 00:05:11,805
But it does take that effort.

34
00:05:14,809 --> 00:05:15,269
Very good.

35
00:05:15,348 --> 00:05:22,737
So, this evening I just wanted to talk about the way the Buddha deconstructs our experience.

36
00:05:22,757 --> 00:05:27,122
So I'm especially aware of people who are new to Buddhism.

37
00:05:28,637 --> 00:05:34,024
so I'll try and keep it fairly straightforward.

38
00:05:35,026 --> 00:05:52,028
The first thing is he talks about, the first thing he gives us cross-sections, so you take a moment and split the human being into various parts, and then he does that in two ways, and he does it in terms of a process.

39
00:05:53,290 --> 00:05:57,716
The process we call dependence origination, and the cross-sections are,

40
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:04,589
are the khandas, the aggregates, and the six consciousnesses.

41
00:06:04,610 --> 00:06:06,112
So these are three that we can look at.

42
00:06:06,892 --> 00:06:14,103
When it comes to the khanda, which means a heap or an aggregate, or a mountain.

43
00:06:14,204 --> 00:06:16,187
See, a mountain is just a collection of stuff.

44
00:06:16,447 --> 00:06:19,812
So if you can imagine, there are these five collections.

45
00:06:20,913 --> 00:06:22,115
The first one is to do with the body.

46
00:06:23,297 --> 00:06:26,521
Now, at a gross level, it's the physical body that we've got.

47
00:06:27,177 --> 00:06:30,841
But at the more subtle level, it's how the mind contacts the body.

48
00:06:32,064 --> 00:06:41,817
And when the mind contacts the body, if you go right down into a feeling, you'll find some combination of these four great elements.

49
00:06:42,817 --> 00:06:46,562
So that's your earth element, fire, water, and air.

50
00:06:47,064 --> 00:06:51,369
The earth element is the weight, the heaviness of it, or the lightness.

51
00:06:52,630 --> 00:06:55,615
The fire element is the temperature you feel.

52
00:06:55,814 --> 00:06:59,098
Cool all the way to boiling hot.

53
00:06:59,117 --> 00:07:03,341
The water element is the elasticity that you feel.

54
00:07:03,663 --> 00:07:09,329
Sometimes when you're watching the breath, perhaps you can feel a sort of an elasticity in it, a cohesion.

55
00:07:11,370 --> 00:07:13,333
So that's the water element.

56
00:07:13,834 --> 00:07:16,476
And the air element, of course, is movement.

57
00:07:18,139 --> 00:07:23,103
And when you go into something like a pain in the knee, for instance,

58
00:07:23,387 --> 00:07:33,341
When you go in there, you see, you may begin to see that actually what you're experiencing are movements, little movements, fire elements, some heat.

59
00:07:35,363 --> 00:07:47,980
When you change your posture and you keep your attention in the knee, you might just find that sort of stretching, that sort of elasticity.

60
00:07:48,000 --> 00:07:52,887
So any combination of these brings you a feeling.

61
00:07:53,223 --> 00:08:00,894
And it's understood that whatever combination it is, we then perceive it as pleasant and unpleasant.

62
00:08:01,053 --> 00:08:01,894
We give it a name.

63
00:08:03,577 --> 00:08:08,223
It gets a bit more subtle with the eyes, which would be seen as more of the fire element.

64
00:08:08,244 --> 00:08:10,567
The ear, of course, as you know, is just pressure.

65
00:08:10,747 --> 00:08:12,189
It's just the earth element.

66
00:08:12,209 --> 00:08:12,810
A movement.

67
00:08:13,952 --> 00:08:21,963
When it comes to taste, of course, it gets even more subtle in terms of trying to describe it with these four elements.

68
00:08:22,365 --> 00:08:36,407
with these four elements, but it's, I mean, you can obviously feel the toughness of the food, the heat of it, the coldness of it, and so on.

69
00:08:36,427 --> 00:08:40,312
So that's the body element, you see, the body heap.

70
00:08:41,355 --> 00:08:44,480
And all that is a given.

71
00:08:44,500 --> 00:08:49,167
You're entirely dependent upon your body for what comes in through the senses.

72
00:08:51,356 --> 00:08:55,722
There's virtually no control over that process.

73
00:08:55,842 --> 00:09:06,759
I mean, you can guard yourself, you needn't put yourself too close to the fire, but the fact is you can't stop the body feeling heat as you approach the fire.

74
00:09:07,198 --> 00:09:08,061
It's just a given.

75
00:09:09,403 --> 00:09:10,703
That's not under our control.

76
00:09:12,427 --> 00:09:14,669
Now that's to be contemplated.

77
00:09:15,991 --> 00:09:16,993
So think about your body.

78
00:09:18,174 --> 00:09:19,677
Do you know now what your liver's doing?

79
00:09:22,407 --> 00:09:27,774
Can you feel red corpuscles being made in the marrow of your bones?

80
00:09:27,794 --> 00:09:33,504
Do you guide them through your bones into the bloodstream?

81
00:09:33,524 --> 00:09:37,250
Have you any idea that as you grow older, the grizzle on the end of your nose is growing?

82
00:09:42,599 --> 00:09:43,419
I doubt you might.

83
00:09:46,032 --> 00:09:47,933
See, there's a whole load of stuff.

84
00:09:47,953 --> 00:09:52,639
You see, when you look at your body, you presume that you are the body, that this is you.

85
00:09:53,198 --> 00:09:57,923
But actually when you investigate your relationship to the body, you find you know nothing.

86
00:10:00,586 --> 00:10:01,827
And you can't do anything about it.

87
00:10:02,089 --> 00:10:05,812
Not after a certain age, anyway.

88
00:10:05,831 --> 00:10:13,500
I'd have loved to have been, you know, tall, lots of hair.

89
00:10:13,519 --> 00:10:15,162
You're just given it, you know.

90
00:10:15,378 --> 00:10:16,259
you may as well be happy.

91
00:10:19,022 --> 00:10:31,774
So that relationship is to be, and what it does, of course, if you suddenly realize that, there is this consciousness, there's this awareness, and it's a sort of alien within this body.

92
00:10:34,898 --> 00:10:34,979
Huh?

93
00:10:34,999 --> 00:10:35,379
Weird.

94
00:10:38,361 --> 00:10:41,826
So that sort of contemplation around the body is well worth it.

95
00:10:41,865 --> 00:10:44,067
And of course, that of course takes you into

96
00:10:44,942 --> 00:10:48,428
The sickness of the body, how the body falls sick, whether you like it or not.

97
00:10:48,769 --> 00:10:49,770
And eventually it's death.

98
00:10:50,451 --> 00:10:51,734
Eventually it's collapse.

99
00:10:52,956 --> 00:10:58,404
So all that contemplation is all around the heap that we call the body, rupa.

100
00:11:00,849 --> 00:11:02,471
The next is to do with feeling.

101
00:11:02,652 --> 00:11:04,815
So from the body we get these feelings.

102
00:11:05,676 --> 00:11:12,267
And feeling is a point where we determine something to be pleasant, unpleasant or neutral.

103
00:11:13,057 --> 00:11:15,740
And there are two types of feelings that we've experienced.

104
00:11:16,721 --> 00:11:18,524
The first one is coming from the body.

105
00:11:18,764 --> 00:11:20,587
So obviously, pain in the knees.

106
00:11:22,551 --> 00:11:26,316
And the other one is coming from our mind, the heart.

107
00:11:26,615 --> 00:11:30,381
In Buddhism, the body and mind are not the same.

108
00:11:30,402 --> 00:11:33,505
They suffer from the same qualities.

109
00:11:33,846 --> 00:11:35,008
They are impermanent.

110
00:11:37,511 --> 00:11:38,614
They're insubstantial.

111
00:11:38,754 --> 00:11:40,716
You can pull it all apart.

112
00:11:40,736 --> 00:11:42,438
They're just energy forms.

113
00:11:42,740 --> 00:11:44,000
but they're two different energies.

114
00:11:45,682 --> 00:11:51,129
And although it doesn't fit in with our modern materialist science, at death they separate.

115
00:11:52,471 --> 00:12:01,360
And whatever is separated out as the mental part, that is the bit that goes on to be reborn into the next moment, whatever it is.

116
00:12:03,182 --> 00:12:05,565
Luckily you don't have to believe this to become fully liberated.

117
00:12:09,369 --> 00:12:11,851
So don't make it a clause, you know.

118
00:12:14,514 --> 00:12:25,875
So, feeling, when we experience feeling, you see, that also is a given.

119
00:12:26,014 --> 00:12:30,403
You know power over changing a feeling as it arises.

120
00:12:30,903 --> 00:12:37,535
You can make yourself feel things, you know, you can stick a pin in your hand if you like doing things like that.

121
00:12:37,852 --> 00:12:44,261
But it's not as though you can stop feelings and sensations arising.

122
00:12:44,282 --> 00:12:46,004
That's also a given.

123
00:12:46,024 --> 00:12:51,412
And it creates a heap, you can say, a heap of all sorts of different types of feelings and sensations.

124
00:12:51,812 --> 00:12:54,797
Some coming from the body, some coming from the heart.

125
00:12:55,918 --> 00:13:00,764
When I say heart-mind, unfortunately in English we've lost this word which connects them.

126
00:13:01,265 --> 00:13:02,528
The old word was soul.

127
00:13:03,129 --> 00:13:07,674
The old split, the old way that we looked at human beings was soul.

128
00:13:07,908 --> 00:13:10,572
Body, soul and spirit.

129
00:13:11,514 --> 00:13:13,375
But now soul has become spirit.

130
00:13:13,976 --> 00:13:16,341
And since our wonderful enlightenment.

131
00:13:16,841 --> 00:13:18,183
And we moved into the mind.

132
00:13:18,605 --> 00:13:20,908
And we lost in a sense contact with the heart.

133
00:13:21,288 --> 00:13:22,931
We now have to say heart mind.

134
00:13:23,893 --> 00:13:25,134
But when you go to the east.

135
00:13:25,154 --> 00:13:27,398
And often when they talk to you.

136
00:13:27,418 --> 00:13:28,620
And they say what do they think.

137
00:13:28,659 --> 00:13:29,961
They point actually to here.

138
00:13:30,722 --> 00:13:32,186
They don't point up here.

139
00:13:32,686 --> 00:13:35,230
Whereas for us the heart is something else.

140
00:13:35,331 --> 00:13:36,312
But I am here.

141
00:13:36,982 --> 00:13:39,667
I am, I think, therefore I am.

142
00:13:39,687 --> 00:13:42,672
That's a bit of a problem for us.

143
00:13:42,971 --> 00:13:58,475
So we've lost that, I mean it's good to have lost that connection in a sense because it allowed us to make all our discoveries and technologies all come from that objectivity.

144
00:13:59,135 --> 00:14:04,965
But unfortunately we've lost contact with the fact that the heart and mind are actually one and the same thing.

145
00:14:05,182 --> 00:14:07,066
The one is firing off the other all the time.

146
00:14:08,769 --> 00:14:17,245
So the feelings that we experience are determined by the body itself, over which we have no control.

147
00:14:17,304 --> 00:14:21,714
The body will give us these feelings when we do these sorts of things.

148
00:14:22,375 --> 00:14:26,363
And the heart will give us these feelings when we act in a certain way.

149
00:14:28,807 --> 00:14:30,509
The next one is all to do with perception.

150
00:14:30,948 --> 00:14:35,273
Now, perception is this amazing ability of the mind to make photocopies.

151
00:14:36,955 --> 00:14:42,419
And what we do is we see something, like an apple for the first time, and it registers.

152
00:14:42,440 --> 00:14:43,761
It registers as a perception.

153
00:14:44,302 --> 00:14:49,147
And then, as we eat more and more apples, our definition of apples grows.

154
00:14:49,287 --> 00:14:54,072
So some are red, some are green, some are soft, some are hard, some are sweet, some are not so sweet, etc.

155
00:14:54,552 --> 00:14:57,294
So that by the end we end up with a concrete definition

156
00:14:57,611 --> 00:14:58,854
concept of an apple.

157
00:15:00,615 --> 00:15:03,780
And all these belong to our memory.

158
00:15:03,801 --> 00:15:09,989
And these perceptions, of course, become very fine in terms of our freedom and democracy and all that sort of stuff.

159
00:15:10,629 --> 00:15:15,977
All these are perceptions which have grown into conceptions, our concepts.

160
00:15:15,998 --> 00:15:23,248
And all that is another heap, another collection of bits which are all

161
00:15:23,465 --> 00:15:24,846
To be separated.

162
00:15:25,126 --> 00:15:27,809
They don't all form one composite.

163
00:15:28,611 --> 00:15:29,493
One thought comes.

164
00:15:29,773 --> 00:15:30,573
It disappears.

165
00:15:30,614 --> 00:15:31,695
Another thought comes.

166
00:15:31,775 --> 00:15:32,416
It disappears.

167
00:15:33,998 --> 00:15:35,760
That's another heap.

168
00:15:35,780 --> 00:15:37,462
And they're not the same as feelings.

169
00:15:37,623 --> 00:15:38,965
And they're not the same as the body.

170
00:15:39,365 --> 00:15:39,966
These are three.

171
00:15:40,767 --> 00:15:41,106
Four.

172
00:15:41,467 --> 00:15:43,610
Three quite distinct heaps.

173
00:15:45,072 --> 00:15:46,014
Now the fourth one.

174
00:15:46,274 --> 00:15:47,054
Is Sankara.

175
00:15:47,534 --> 00:15:48,917
Which translates as.

176
00:15:49,577 --> 00:15:51,159
Volitional conditioning.

177
00:15:51,847 --> 00:15:57,698
That would be the old regular way of translating it.

178
00:15:58,419 --> 00:16:03,068
Other people have tried various things like concoctions and stuff like that.

179
00:16:03,089 --> 00:16:06,875
But I think we get close to what we mean by that when we talk about habits.

180
00:16:08,278 --> 00:16:13,629
Now this is where, see the Buddha's trying to separate out for us where the problem lies.

181
00:16:14,190 --> 00:16:15,072
Remember he's only...

182
00:16:15,322 --> 00:16:18,326
His only concern is to teach suffering and the end of suffering.

183
00:16:18,346 --> 00:16:18,885
That's it.

184
00:16:19,046 --> 00:16:20,607
You know, when he's asked what does he teach?

185
00:16:20,928 --> 00:16:22,070
Does he teach about God?

186
00:16:22,129 --> 00:16:23,951
Does he teach about the universe?

187
00:16:23,971 --> 00:16:28,418
He says, no, he says, I only teach about suffering and the end of suffering.

188
00:16:28,437 --> 00:16:30,480
Unsatisfactoriness and the end of satisfactoriness.

189
00:16:30,500 --> 00:16:38,129
So, the reason why we are deconstructing ourselves is not just for the fun of it, it's to find out where the problem lies.

190
00:16:38,149 --> 00:16:40,532
The problem lies right here in Sankara.

191
00:16:41,253 --> 00:16:43,034
Sankara means volitional conditioning.

192
00:16:43,416 --> 00:16:45,278
So, it's the volitional bit

193
00:16:45,679 --> 00:16:46,341
Right?

194
00:16:46,360 --> 00:16:47,621
Which is the important bit.

195
00:16:47,642 --> 00:16:56,793
It's the bit where we're making decisions based upon wrong understandings that are causing Sankara's habits.

196
00:16:56,813 --> 00:17:03,861
Causing certain habits which include both the emotional feelings and the thought feelings.

197
00:17:04,143 --> 00:17:05,604
And it creates a habit.

198
00:17:05,845 --> 00:17:06,265
A habit.

199
00:17:06,384 --> 00:17:08,508
A way of expressing ourselves.

200
00:17:10,109 --> 00:17:13,713
And some habits that we have are beautiful and some are not so beautiful.

201
00:17:14,154 --> 00:17:14,234
See?

202
00:17:14,451 --> 00:17:21,663
But the important thing about this particular heap that's in us is that it is being created by our will.

203
00:17:22,124 --> 00:17:24,929
This is what we can take control of.

204
00:17:24,949 --> 00:17:30,978
When we say we can take control of it, the bit that's already been created, you can't do anything about.

205
00:17:31,358 --> 00:17:32,981
That's what we're suffering when we sit here.

206
00:17:33,041 --> 00:17:38,671
All the sadness and the anger and occasionally a bit of joy.

207
00:17:38,711 --> 00:17:42,096
So all that stuff that's come up,

208
00:17:42,480 --> 00:18:09,635
that's a consequence of past decision making and all we can do with that is bear with it and make sure we don't indulge it because every time we indulge it we empower it again and that's the process of will so when you're doing your standing meditation for instance and you're standing still and you're saying to yourself intending to walk intending to walk see stay there for a while with that intending which is another way of saying desiring okay

209
00:18:09,903 --> 00:18:12,265
So intending to just feel the energy there.

210
00:18:12,625 --> 00:18:14,948
Feel the energy and how the body wants to move.

211
00:18:15,969 --> 00:18:20,011
And then suddenly there's a decision and the foot moves.

212
00:18:20,031 --> 00:18:23,434
What is it that's brought something out of potential into an actual?

213
00:18:24,155 --> 00:18:24,756
That's the will.

214
00:18:26,258 --> 00:18:28,380
And you can't separate the will from the action.

215
00:18:29,180 --> 00:18:33,805
So the Buddha says, what I call karma, an act, is the will.

216
00:18:36,007 --> 00:18:39,690
It's a bit like, as far as I know, and I stand to be corrected of course,

217
00:18:40,025 --> 00:18:44,490
It's when you throw a stone into the air, you can't separate the force from the stone.

218
00:18:46,453 --> 00:18:50,579
And what is it anyway?

219
00:18:50,599 --> 00:18:52,903
You can't separate force from the object that is moving.

220
00:18:54,506 --> 00:18:54,885
Interesting.

221
00:18:56,327 --> 00:18:56,788
Am I right?

222
00:18:57,430 --> 00:18:58,592
Is there a scientist amongst us?

223
00:19:01,134 --> 00:19:02,696
If I've made it up, forgive me.

224
00:19:05,421 --> 00:19:09,406
I read it somewhere years ago.

225
00:19:09,656 --> 00:19:39,461
the thing is in science it changes so much you don't know where you're at so you've got that candor that heap, that aggregate the last one is consciousness and consciousness is the ability of the mind to hold an image for us that's what consciousness is, like a screen and it holds the image and that image is multi-dimensional and that image holds feelings, it holds everything

226
00:19:39,981 --> 00:19:42,724
and it holds it long enough for it to be registered.

227
00:19:43,464 --> 00:19:48,269
If it's not registered, we hardly know it, we hardly see it, we're hardly aware of it.

228
00:19:48,809 --> 00:19:52,874
But when it registers, it's there for the moment, and then it passes away.

229
00:19:53,595 --> 00:19:59,960
And consciousness is arising at tremendous speed, and it's giving us the impression of continuity.

230
00:20:01,942 --> 00:20:09,229
So, for instance, when we are watching, say, a film or something,

231
00:20:09,833 --> 00:20:14,820
We can hear, we can hear the conversation, we can see what's going on.

232
00:20:15,922 --> 00:20:21,109
We're drinking coffee and tea, or popcorn, or whatever it is, and we can taste it.

233
00:20:21,691 --> 00:20:25,416
All that seems to us to be happening at the same time.

234
00:20:26,278 --> 00:20:37,275
But in Buddhist psychology, what's happening is, moment after moment, consciousnesses are arising at some tremendous speed, and it gives us a sense...

235
00:20:37,576 --> 00:21:05,912
an experience of continuity and the closest we can as a good image for that is the old film where it was framed 26 frames or something or 25 frames a minute and it gave us the impression of continuity it gave us the impression of continuity and as soon as it slowed down you realise actually it was just these moments of flashing images on a screen and that's how consciousness works see

236
00:21:06,971 --> 00:21:15,583
Now, when you pull yourself out into the position of the observer, all that is becoming an object.

237
00:21:16,845 --> 00:21:25,355
Before we came to meditation, before we came to this, we would have just presumed ourselves to be this human being.

238
00:21:26,798 --> 00:21:28,579
You wouldn't have made an object of yourself.

239
00:21:28,599 --> 00:21:33,807
You'd have been aware that, for instance, you've got a pain in the knee or a pain in the head, but there wouldn't have been that

240
00:21:34,073 --> 00:21:38,778
that separation of the knowing from what's being known.

241
00:21:40,380 --> 00:21:48,410
And there would have been a real attachment to your body in terms of its illness and whatnot.

242
00:21:48,430 --> 00:21:54,797
Now, in the meditation, what we're doing is, we are pulling something out of these five aggregates.

243
00:21:55,998 --> 00:21:59,201
And we're making these five aggregates objects to observe.

244
00:22:00,804 --> 00:22:03,507
That which is pulling out, you see, is...

245
00:22:04,059 --> 00:22:07,664
your intuitive awareness.

246
00:22:07,684 --> 00:22:19,320
Now that doesn't mean to say that once we've begun to practice this and see this that suddenly we become totally equanimous and content and you can stab me in the back and I'll be fine.

247
00:22:19,842 --> 00:22:21,704
No it's not.

248
00:22:21,724 --> 00:22:29,434
But at least there is within us this inkling of a knowledge that there is something which doesn't belong to the five candles.

249
00:22:29,675 --> 00:22:31,417
That is this human being.

250
00:22:33,153 --> 00:22:43,547
So that's one way that the Buddha deconstructs our experience.

251
00:22:43,988 --> 00:22:46,230
I'm going to connect all this to Dependent Origination.

252
00:22:46,632 --> 00:22:50,016
Oh heavens, it's 10 past 7.

253
00:22:50,557 --> 00:22:51,438
I've only just started.

254
00:22:55,323 --> 00:22:57,185
I might have to...

255
00:22:57,587 --> 00:23:01,834
I'll finish with this because I hate going on and on.

256
00:23:01,854 --> 00:23:06,000
And then tomorrow I'll sort of go into dependent origination.

257
00:23:06,059 --> 00:23:08,442
Yes, that's what I'll do.

258
00:23:08,462 --> 00:23:13,529
The next way that he deconstructs our experience is looking at our sense bases.

259
00:23:14,751 --> 00:23:17,275
And the sense bases in Buddhism are six.

260
00:23:17,875 --> 00:23:20,859
The five that we obviously know.

261
00:23:21,280 --> 00:23:22,422
And the sixth is the mind.

262
00:23:24,404 --> 00:23:26,768
In the psychology of Buddhism, when

263
00:23:27,186 --> 00:23:37,896
When you hear something, actually what is being received at the sense door is pressure.

264
00:23:37,916 --> 00:23:39,999
There is no sound, right?

265
00:23:40,019 --> 00:23:43,301
There's no sound in the universe, okay?

266
00:23:43,362 --> 00:23:47,006
And there's no light in the universe, right?

267
00:23:47,046 --> 00:23:49,929
You have to have these senses to hear something.

268
00:23:50,469 --> 00:23:53,211
And you have to have these senses to see something.

269
00:23:53,231 --> 00:23:56,755
So when the airways begin to touch upon the eardrum,

270
00:23:57,307 --> 00:24:03,255
They are little messages, little stimulus going in.

271
00:24:04,336 --> 00:24:07,519
And that's all the ear actually does.

272
00:24:08,980 --> 00:24:16,029
From then on, it's taken into the mind, and there's a process of recognition.

273
00:24:16,049 --> 00:24:17,391
So, bell.

274
00:24:18,712 --> 00:24:21,095
Yeah, bell.

275
00:24:21,154 --> 00:24:22,557
Just the sound of a bell.

276
00:24:23,228 --> 00:24:28,634
Then when the process of the bell is completed, there's the understanding of what a bell means.

277
00:24:29,895 --> 00:24:30,016
Right?

278
00:24:30,036 --> 00:24:35,221
Then the bell is put into a time slot where you understand that it's an awakening bell.

279
00:24:36,223 --> 00:24:41,809
And then, only then, at the end of that process, does the eye come in and say, I've got to get up.

280
00:24:43,071 --> 00:24:43,192
Right?

281
00:24:43,211 --> 00:24:45,394
That whole process is one after the other.

282
00:24:45,694 --> 00:24:47,777
And believe it or not, you can actually experience that.

283
00:24:50,160 --> 00:24:52,542
That can be experienced, but you've got to...

284
00:24:52,961 --> 00:24:57,006
You've got to really get down to your meditation today.

285
00:24:57,026 --> 00:24:58,227
You've got to be really on the ball.

286
00:24:58,646 --> 00:25:00,308
But that's how deep you can go.

287
00:25:00,388 --> 00:25:10,196
You can actually see these momentary consciousnesses and how the mind actually creates everything from this original, very simple stimulus.

288
00:25:11,258 --> 00:25:13,680
Now it's the same with seeing.

289
00:25:13,700 --> 00:25:21,146
I'm sure you've seen these diagrams which show you that when we look at a picture, the eye is darting all over the place.

290
00:25:21,666 --> 00:25:22,468
It's never still.

291
00:25:22,807 --> 00:25:26,373
It's quite amazing to see how the eye is just moving.

292
00:25:26,393 --> 00:25:27,674
But we don't experience that.

293
00:25:27,694 --> 00:25:30,618
What we experience is the picture.

294
00:25:30,638 --> 00:25:33,321
And of course we can focus on different parts of the picture.

295
00:25:33,782 --> 00:25:40,171
And we still are not aware of the fact that even then the eye is moving at tremendous speeds all over it, picking up little pixels.

296
00:25:42,233 --> 00:25:43,776
And even that can be seen.

297
00:25:44,531 --> 00:25:53,624
Even that, you can actually be looking at something and it all frazzles up into a sort of, you know these Pantelist paintings?

298
00:25:53,644 --> 00:25:55,727
You know these where they paint with little dots?

299
00:25:56,728 --> 00:25:58,309
Shivering like that in front of you.

300
00:25:58,329 --> 00:26:01,054
And then it congeals into a picture.

301
00:26:01,074 --> 00:26:06,961
And that means that this mind, the actual perceiving mind, is right up against the sense door.

302
00:26:09,810 --> 00:26:16,779
Now, the purpose that the Buddha again points this out is that each Zen store is individual and discreet.

303
00:26:17,280 --> 00:26:19,324
You simply cannot smell through your eyes.

304
00:26:21,326 --> 00:26:30,198
And therefore, the way that we experience the world is in these discreet moments, seeing, hearing, smelling, touching.

305
00:26:30,838 --> 00:26:37,708
And somehow the mind, at a deeper level of its processing, can put it all together into an experiencing.

306
00:26:39,240 --> 00:26:39,761
Here we go.

307
00:26:40,762 --> 00:26:41,403
Say your prayers.

308
00:26:51,057 --> 00:26:51,718
It's just pressure.

309
00:26:52,898 --> 00:26:53,180
Just pressure.

310
00:26:53,200 --> 00:26:53,279
Yes.

311
00:26:53,299 --> 00:26:54,201
It's just pressure waves.

312
00:26:55,942 --> 00:27:03,634
So that's a specific way that the Buddha also deconstructs our experience.

313
00:27:03,653 --> 00:27:05,316
So here we have two ways of deconstructing.

314
00:27:05,785 --> 00:27:07,426
And what's the purpose of it?

315
00:27:07,626 --> 00:27:11,810
It's to take away the sense of substance.

316
00:27:11,830 --> 00:27:14,094
It's to take away the sense of me.

317
00:27:14,653 --> 00:27:14,934
Me.

318
00:27:17,696 --> 00:27:24,023
And again, in that process of observing what's coming in, of actually being at the process of hearing.

319
00:27:24,124 --> 00:27:31,030
So when you're outside, just to stand there with that spacious awareness, putting your attention entirely upon one of the ears.

320
00:27:31,731 --> 00:27:32,031
You see?

321
00:27:32,833 --> 00:27:34,074
And just hearing, hearing.

322
00:27:34,094 --> 00:27:35,556
And just keep it there, steady.

323
00:27:36,700 --> 00:27:42,006
When you're looking, just keep your eyes steady on the flower and just watch the perceptual process.

324
00:27:43,247 --> 00:27:44,087
Watch the eye doing.

325
00:27:44,327 --> 00:27:50,275
So you're always, as it were, standing one step behind yourself to see process.

326
00:27:51,976 --> 00:27:53,758
Nothing remains.

327
00:27:54,278 --> 00:27:54,759
Remember that.

328
00:27:54,898 --> 00:27:56,260
Everything's in a process.

329
00:27:56,300 --> 00:27:57,241
Everything's changing.

330
00:27:57,942 --> 00:28:02,948
And it's to be able to stand still enough to be able to see that.

331
00:28:02,968 --> 00:28:04,750
And in our meditation, we're trying to

332
00:28:04,914 --> 00:28:09,060
Trying to constantly access that point of stillness within us.

333
00:28:09,080 --> 00:28:11,885
The observation post, the observer, the knower.

334
00:28:13,086 --> 00:28:23,923
See, so that constant effort to come off the thinking mind and to bring ourselves back to the direct experience at the sense basis of this particular moment.

335
00:28:25,205 --> 00:28:27,169
Always feeling, always in the body.

336
00:28:27,930 --> 00:28:29,251
Ground yourself in the body.

337
00:28:30,952 --> 00:28:39,926
And in this way, the sharpness, the discriminative faculty of this intuitive awareness becomes finer and finer.

338
00:28:42,130 --> 00:28:48,140
So, in a sense, if you really want to deepen your practice, you've got to make that effort of continuity.

339
00:28:49,402 --> 00:28:52,946
So you can't be, you have to give up cups of tea for a start.

340
00:28:53,667 --> 00:28:59,356
You've got to make the effort to, from here to the walking place,

341
00:28:59,776 --> 00:29:00,056
right?

342
00:29:00,096 --> 00:29:01,137
There's your objective.

343
00:29:01,419 --> 00:29:02,921
Your objective is the walking place.

344
00:29:03,201 --> 00:29:06,887
You bring yourself back here and every footstep is known.

345
00:29:06,907 --> 00:29:08,069
Every footstep is felt.

346
00:29:08,671 --> 00:29:11,596
And then you stop and you do your walking meditation, right?

347
00:29:11,615 --> 00:29:19,169
And you might start with a bit of an exercise, just going up and down quite rapidly to get the energy up and just to relax.

348
00:29:19,529 --> 00:29:22,474
And then slower and slower and slower, you see?

349
00:29:22,935 --> 00:29:25,480
Very, very slow, watching every movement, you see?

350
00:29:26,017 --> 00:29:30,423
And then when the bell goes, to come in at a speed where you don't lose that collectedness.

351
00:29:34,148 --> 00:29:38,394
Now there's the true meditator.

352
00:29:38,434 --> 00:29:42,101
This afternoon I walked out there and there were two meditators sunbathing.

353
00:29:46,227 --> 00:29:48,951
I thought, well that's the pits.

354
00:29:53,557 --> 00:29:55,180
They're obviously not suffering enough.

355
00:29:56,054 --> 00:29:58,175
Because if you're suffering enough, you want to get rid of it.

356
00:29:58,195 --> 00:30:08,145
So I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

357
00:30:08,465 --> 00:30:10,968
I will, of course, carry on deconstructing tomorrow.

358
00:30:11,689 --> 00:30:23,259
And by your fierce and determined effort, I'm sure you will make plenty of insights that will bring you to your liberation sooner rather than later.

359
00:30:24,943 --> 00:30:31,974
So if you'd like to take a break.

360
00:30:31,994 --> 00:30:32,756
I have to apologise.

361
00:30:32,796 --> 00:30:35,220
Yesterday, when I looked at the clock, it was ten past seven.

362
00:30:36,142 --> 00:30:40,528
And I should have gone on, it was nearly quarter past, and I should have gone on until half past.

363
00:30:40,608 --> 00:30:49,122
But I was working on the time that we keep at Sadi Panya, where everything's half an hour early, and where we rise at 3.30, which is the proper time.

364
00:30:51,786 --> 00:30:52,807
So, I've got...

365
00:30:53,125 --> 00:30:58,490
I got confused, so maybe I'll just extend a little bit if I don't finish what I need to say.

366
00:30:59,952 --> 00:31:04,877
So we were talking about this whole process of deconstructing.

367
00:31:05,058 --> 00:31:12,446
Remember that even in objects, you take a car.

368
00:31:13,508 --> 00:31:17,833
When you're driving, for those of you who drive, there are times when you and the car are one.

369
00:31:18,505 --> 00:31:26,515
You don't experience yourself as separate from the car because you're totally involved or absorbed into the action of driving.

370
00:31:27,096 --> 00:31:31,280
Especially when there's a tricky corner or somebody's doing something nasty to you.

371
00:31:33,124 --> 00:31:35,386
And then you wake up and there you are in the car.

372
00:31:36,428 --> 00:31:39,090
And you still think you have control over the car.

373
00:31:39,111 --> 00:31:40,113
And then suddenly it stops.

374
00:31:41,173 --> 00:31:44,218
And then you realise that actually your control is superficial.

375
00:31:44,317 --> 00:31:45,640
You can move it this way and that way.

376
00:31:45,660 --> 00:31:47,541
You can back it up and back it into somebody.

377
00:31:48,063 --> 00:31:48,343
But

378
00:31:48,661 --> 00:31:52,348
You can't actually do anything about the inner workings of the car.

379
00:31:53,270 --> 00:31:56,397
So that's the situation that we find ourselves within this body.

380
00:31:57,098 --> 00:31:59,865
We can move our arms about and wave them and all that sort of stuff.

381
00:32:00,425 --> 00:32:02,009
You can't make your arm grow any longer.

382
00:32:03,211 --> 00:32:05,336
You can't do much with the body as it is.

383
00:32:05,586 --> 00:32:12,076
And when we look into the workings of a car, especially a modern car, it's quite mystifying, at least to me.

384
00:32:13,778 --> 00:32:17,784
I once thought of myself as a bit of a mechanic because I pulled engines apart.

385
00:32:18,184 --> 00:32:21,990
And about four or five years ago, a friend of mine stopped.

386
00:32:22,351 --> 00:32:23,712
The car just stopped.

387
00:32:24,314 --> 00:32:26,277
And I was with him.

388
00:32:26,497 --> 00:32:27,939
And we opened the bonnet.

389
00:32:28,138 --> 00:32:32,665
And I said, oh, it sounds to me like it's the distributor.

390
00:32:32,685 --> 00:32:34,969
And I pointed to the distributor, you see.

391
00:32:35,201 --> 00:32:37,525
I said, you know, we'd better call the RAC.

392
00:32:37,545 --> 00:32:42,411
So the RAC came over, and he looked in, and it was just a fan belt.

393
00:32:43,132 --> 00:32:47,817
And mysteriously, the distributor had moved to the other side of the engine.

394
00:32:47,838 --> 00:32:50,982
So I don't quite know how that happened.

395
00:32:51,743 --> 00:32:57,191
Anyway, so you see how delusional he is.

396
00:32:57,211 --> 00:32:58,172
So...

397
00:32:58,961 --> 00:33:07,170
So it's that business of recognizing that we're in this very strange situation of being in the body, but not of the body.

398
00:33:07,910 --> 00:33:11,973
And what is it that's in the body that's not of the body?

399
00:33:11,993 --> 00:33:21,983
So through the process of deconstruction, the Buddha's trying to make us investigate the way it really is, not the way we presume it to be, through our delusion.

400
00:33:22,604 --> 00:33:26,708
The delusion is, I am this person, I am this body.

401
00:33:27,970 --> 00:33:35,044
Now, as I think I've mentioned before, you know how deluded you are about your body when the doctor tells you you've got six weeks to live.

402
00:33:35,084 --> 00:33:38,369
Then there's freak out.

403
00:33:38,390 --> 00:33:47,769
And that level of paranoia and fear around death is the measure of our identification with the body.

404
00:33:49,392 --> 00:33:49,471
See?

405
00:33:50,836 --> 00:33:59,243
So, in these five aggregates, these five heaps, he's trying to separate out, and he's telling us, in a sense, what's the given.

406
00:33:59,644 --> 00:34:00,625
The body's the given.

407
00:34:01,425 --> 00:34:02,527
Perceptions are given.

408
00:34:02,708 --> 00:34:05,369
It's part of that whole psychological process.

409
00:34:05,951 --> 00:34:07,172
Feelings are given.

410
00:34:07,192 --> 00:34:13,338
But in the sankara, these conditions, here we have a measure of control.

411
00:34:14,838 --> 00:34:18,682
Sankara are conditions, and they are conditioning.

412
00:34:19,068 --> 00:34:34,467
So when you have, shall we say, the habit of getting really excited about something, as soon as that something that you get excited about comes up, the excitement will come, because that's how you've trained yourself.

413
00:34:34,528 --> 00:34:36,030
You've trained yourself to be excited.

414
00:34:36,710 --> 00:34:43,400
But in the coming up of the excitement, the excitement itself is developing itself.

415
00:34:43,420 --> 00:34:45,463
So all these habits that we have,

416
00:34:45,864 --> 00:35:03,905
whether it's the fear of things, anxiety, depression, joy, falling in love, all that sort of stuff is something that we've conditioned ourselves and when it becomes active, it is conditioning.

417
00:35:03,925 --> 00:35:07,309
So conditions are not stable.

418
00:35:08,030 --> 00:35:15,719
And our understanding is to catch where the intentionality is because it's at that point we still have a choice.

419
00:35:16,476 --> 00:35:19,081
We can either indulge it or let it go.

420
00:35:19,481 --> 00:35:21,684
Or, in some cases of course, develop it.

421
00:35:21,985 --> 00:35:25,110
If it's something beautiful, then we should develop it.

422
00:35:26,371 --> 00:35:33,342
So he points to the Sankara as the place where we have to really look as to where suffering arises.

423
00:35:34,304 --> 00:35:35,646
Pain arises in the body.

424
00:35:37,128 --> 00:35:39,793
Pain arises from the Sankara in the body.

425
00:35:39,813 --> 00:35:42,777
That's where you get emotional disturbances within us.

426
00:35:42,818 --> 00:35:43,699
That's a given.

427
00:35:44,235 --> 00:35:47,079
But what do we mean by suffering?

428
00:35:47,599 --> 00:35:50,360
Suffering is our relationship to what's happening.

429
00:35:51,583 --> 00:35:53,423
And that's all within the Sankharas.

430
00:35:54,784 --> 00:36:09,679
When these Sankharas go into the memory, Sanya, that's when they produce this lovely word, Papancha, proliferation.

431
00:36:10,840 --> 00:36:13,382
The Buddha points out when these Sankharas arise,

432
00:36:13,682 --> 00:36:16,907
They go into your memory and they start producing a story.

433
00:36:17,208 --> 00:36:19,972
And it's through the story that they develop themselves.

434
00:36:19,992 --> 00:36:22,956
That's why in Vipassana we're constantly coming off the mind.

435
00:36:23,996 --> 00:36:25,119
Coming back into the body.

436
00:36:27,402 --> 00:36:29,445
And the final one of course is this consciousness.

437
00:36:29,644 --> 00:36:31,967
So there's your five khandhas.

438
00:36:32,489 --> 00:36:36,755
And then we talked about the five sense bases.

439
00:36:38,056 --> 00:36:41,360
And how each consciousness is

440
00:36:41,728 --> 00:36:43,751
Is confined to a sense base.

441
00:36:44,632 --> 00:36:45,893
In Buddhist understanding.

442
00:36:46,393 --> 00:36:47,974
An eye consciousness arises.

443
00:36:48,255 --> 00:36:48,835
And that's all.

444
00:36:49,155 --> 00:36:51,038
And then a hearing consciousness arises.

445
00:36:51,498 --> 00:36:52,059
And that's all.

446
00:36:52,739 --> 00:36:53,500
So although we.

447
00:36:53,681 --> 00:36:56,023
Because of the speed of these consciousnesses.

448
00:36:56,103 --> 00:36:58,025
We get the sense of it all being one.

449
00:36:58,846 --> 00:37:00,367
And all being continuous.

450
00:37:01,949 --> 00:37:02,949
That's the delusion.

451
00:37:03,170 --> 00:37:04,771
So in our practice.

452
00:37:05,532 --> 00:37:07,094
We're constantly moving.

453
00:37:07,853 --> 00:37:09,215
Down deeper and deeper.

454
00:37:09,695 --> 00:37:11,137
What we mean by deeper here.

455
00:37:11,418 --> 00:37:11,617
Is.

456
00:37:11,833 --> 00:37:13,675
Less and less time slot.

457
00:37:14,677 --> 00:37:17,519
How long is a moment in time?

458
00:37:19,221 --> 00:37:21,003
How long do you experience a moment?

459
00:37:25,306 --> 00:37:26,108
Interesting question, no?

460
00:37:26,128 --> 00:37:27,969
I mean, how long is it?

461
00:37:28,050 --> 00:37:28,990
Is it half a second?

462
00:37:29,030 --> 00:37:29,711
Is it a second?

463
00:37:29,811 --> 00:37:31,853
How long is a moment, you see?

464
00:37:32,333 --> 00:37:39,041
And what we're doing is, we are bringing our attention slowly and slowly.

465
00:37:39,260 --> 00:37:41,182
See, there's a noting and the attention.

466
00:37:41,467 --> 00:37:42,688
The noting of the attention.

467
00:37:43,028 --> 00:37:45,213
And then we're locked into the moment.

468
00:37:45,753 --> 00:37:47,476
The noting stops.

469
00:37:47,496 --> 00:37:52,043
That's if you develop that concentration well enough.

470
00:37:52,563 --> 00:37:59,173
And then in that moment, it's as though time collapses into that actual present moment.

471
00:38:00,936 --> 00:38:05,483
And that's when you realize that actually these moments are infinitesimally small.

472
00:38:06,405 --> 00:38:08,367
Even there, even there,

473
00:38:09,056 --> 00:38:29,766
will have some sort of measure because you're not actually seeing the arising and passing away of individual consciousnesses see so that's our practice is to the sort of Theravada approach you might say is not so much the spaciousness but the minuscule you know

474
00:38:30,150 --> 00:38:30,871
What is it?

475
00:38:30,891 --> 00:38:32,434
The universe in a grain of sand.

476
00:38:33,275 --> 00:38:35,958
It's actually going down to the minuscule moment.

477
00:38:36,498 --> 00:38:39,302
And that's where we're constantly driving the attention.

478
00:38:41,085 --> 00:38:41,184
Okay?

479
00:38:43,487 --> 00:38:48,873
Now, those two ways of looking at this deconstruction process are cross-sections.

480
00:38:49,315 --> 00:38:58,967
You can take any moment in a human being's life, draw a line, and you'll find the five heaps, the five aggregates, and the five consciousnesses.

481
00:38:59,166 --> 00:38:59,887
One or the other, I mean.

482
00:39:01,217 --> 00:39:10,144
Now, when he tries to deconstruct the timeline of how we create suffering, that's what he's interested in, remember, just suffering.

483
00:39:12,070 --> 00:39:13,856
We have dependent origination.

484
00:39:13,876 --> 00:39:14,940
And this seems to have been...

485
00:39:15,358 --> 00:39:17,382
completely new to the age.

486
00:39:17,422 --> 00:39:20,347
There's nothing like it, seemingly, before the Buddha.

487
00:39:20,487 --> 00:39:22,931
This is what the academics tell you.

488
00:39:23,592 --> 00:39:34,833
So it's a real deep insight into how we create the world that we're living in and where the mistakes come.

489
00:39:34,853 --> 00:39:40,842
Now, if you look at that chanting sheet, you'll be able to follow me because I'm just going to go through the dependent origination.

490
00:39:50,340 --> 00:39:56,251
So that's in the middle of the puja, middle of the puja sheet, the morning puja sheet, that's what you want.

491
00:39:58,235 --> 00:39:59,155
And it's in the middle of it.

492
00:40:00,237 --> 00:40:09,112
And you'll notice that it starts off with the Buddha's victory verse.

493
00:40:10,235 --> 00:40:14,862
Victory verse, you see, he says, let me get my goggles on.

494
00:40:20,648 --> 00:40:22,791
Can't wait for summer when I get my other operation.

495
00:40:22,811 --> 00:40:23,592
I'll be able to see anything.

496
00:40:24,532 --> 00:40:31,081
Now then, he says, Seeking but not finding the house builder.

497
00:40:31,442 --> 00:40:35,067
Okay, so this house builder is this I, this self.

498
00:40:36,289 --> 00:40:38,891
I have travelled through the round of countless births.

499
00:40:38,952 --> 00:40:40,875
How painful is birth over and over again.

500
00:40:41,094 --> 00:40:43,639
Oh house builder, I have now caught you.

501
00:40:44,280 --> 00:40:45,961
I shall not build a house again.

502
00:40:46,141 --> 00:40:47,664
Your rafters have been broken.

503
00:40:47,724 --> 00:40:49,025
Your ridge pole demolished.

504
00:40:49,507 --> 00:40:49,606
Okay.

505
00:40:49,626 --> 00:40:49,726
Okay.

506
00:40:49,994 --> 00:40:53,318
So there he's talking about this self, this construct of a person.

507
00:40:54,099 --> 00:40:55,179
And what does he come up with?

508
00:40:55,380 --> 00:40:58,744
What does he attain through that?

509
00:40:58,804 --> 00:41:02,527
He attains a consciousness which is unconditioned.

510
00:41:02,547 --> 00:41:03,929
We should go into that a bit later.

511
00:41:04,469 --> 00:41:07,574
And all craving, all the defilements have gone.

512
00:41:08,235 --> 00:41:10,717
So that's the process that we're into now.

513
00:41:10,737 --> 00:41:19,106
We're into this process of finding out who the house builder is, what the house builder is, getting rid of it, destroying the house, and ending up perfectly happy and wonderful.

514
00:41:20,182 --> 00:41:20,784
It's worth it, isn't it?

515
00:41:21,304 --> 00:41:22,025
All this suffering.

516
00:41:24,449 --> 00:41:29,155
So it begins with this word avidya and it's often translated as ignorance.

517
00:41:30,378 --> 00:41:32,380
But it's not a culpable ignorance.

518
00:41:32,400 --> 00:41:34,623
We've just landed into a place of not knowing.

519
00:41:35,184 --> 00:41:40,311
So if you think of a baby, you see, when we're born, there we are, we scream a little bundle of cells.

520
00:41:40,813 --> 00:41:41,333
What do we know?

521
00:41:41,393 --> 00:41:45,278
So go back to that moment of being born, you see.

522
00:41:46,320 --> 00:41:47,322
We don't know anything.

523
00:41:47,672 --> 00:41:52,019
From then on, the information starts coming in, and we start building up the world.

524
00:41:52,960 --> 00:42:01,074
As you know, well, some of you might know, the wonderful worker Margaret Marler, who was a student of Freud, studied children up to the age of three.

525
00:42:01,875 --> 00:42:05,541
And later studies, of course, confirmed her findings.

526
00:42:06,021 --> 00:42:12,110
For up to the age of four months, all we experience is a bath of...

527
00:42:12,597 --> 00:42:14,019
Of sensations.

528
00:42:14,239 --> 00:42:15,021
There's no depth to it.

529
00:42:15,041 --> 00:42:16,003
There's no 3D.

530
00:42:16,403 --> 00:42:18,246
That's why you see children reaching out for things.

531
00:42:18,266 --> 00:42:20,190
They're actually creating a 3D world.

532
00:42:21,092 --> 00:42:33,275
And then from four months onwards, it seems, the first object, something looms out of this me, this, I mean, there's no concept of me, this me that I'm experiencing, and it's usually your carer, your mother, usually.

533
00:42:33,795 --> 00:42:36,681
And slowly, that outer world gets pushed out.

534
00:42:37,048 --> 00:42:42,474
And it's not until the age of three that you're actually clear that I am me and everything else is not me.

535
00:42:43,155 --> 00:42:44,416
I'm a boy, I'm a girl.

536
00:42:44,516 --> 00:42:46,518
You know, that's the moment, round about three.

537
00:42:47,681 --> 00:42:50,362
That's how long it takes to separate the outside world.

538
00:42:50,384 --> 00:42:52,666
Now, all we're doing is the same inwardly.

539
00:42:53,467 --> 00:42:56,710
We're just pushing the inner world out to make it an object.

540
00:43:00,675 --> 00:43:03,697
Now, the ignorance is to think that we are this inner world.

541
00:43:04,623 --> 00:43:07,065
with its emotions, thoughts, etc., etc.

542
00:43:07,905 --> 00:43:13,831
Now, that abidja, be careful, it's not a culpable English, right?

543
00:43:13,871 --> 00:43:15,532
We're not guilty, right?

544
00:43:15,552 --> 00:43:19,117
Which is a relief, I think, for love.

545
00:43:19,137 --> 00:43:22,300
We're not existentially guilty, right?

546
00:43:22,320 --> 00:43:27,324
We never did nothing wrong before becoming ignorant.

547
00:43:27,344 --> 00:43:28,545
We just didn't know.

548
00:43:29,045 --> 00:43:30,987
I did find a word which means not knowing.

549
00:43:31,327 --> 00:43:34,190
The word is nescience, but nobody knows it, so I don't

550
00:43:34,728 --> 00:43:37,152
I only point out that there is a word for not knowing.

551
00:43:38,574 --> 00:43:48,751
So this Avijja Pachya Sankara, Sankara Pachya, so all he's saying is be out of this, out of this position of not knowing, we've created these conditions.

552
00:43:50,715 --> 00:43:52,097
These habits, right?

553
00:43:52,117 --> 00:43:52,938
That's all he's saying.

554
00:43:53,407 --> 00:43:58,132
And then, Sankara Pachavinyana.

555
00:43:58,572 --> 00:44:08,342
Now, it's out of the body-mind complex, remember, there arises this ability to hold things on a screen.

556
00:44:09,123 --> 00:44:12,885
Now, if there was nothing there to be held on a screen, there'd be no screen.

557
00:44:13,726 --> 00:44:22,014
So, for instance, when in deep sleep, there's no obvious consciousness because there's nothing coming up, awakening, as it were, on that screen.

558
00:44:22,315 --> 00:44:27,322
But it's because of these sankhara that the screen is, shall we say, brightened up.

559
00:44:28,063 --> 00:44:29,545
And this screen is consciousness.

560
00:44:30,126 --> 00:44:39,018
And consciousness, remember, see, English words don't really catch it because these days academics and scientists are studying consciousness.

561
00:44:39,038 --> 00:44:41,782
I mean, that's the end of clarity for about 100 years.

562
00:44:42,402 --> 00:44:43,885
So it's basically...

563
00:44:44,371 --> 00:45:02,813
In Buddhist understanding, if you think of consciousness like a 3D, a three-dimensional hologram which you can see, and in it there are feelings, images, thoughts, the whole damn thing is there, can be held within that consciousness.

564
00:45:05,436 --> 00:45:08,099
So it's not to be confused with sati.

565
00:45:08,670 --> 00:45:11,653
See, this is the important thing.

566
00:45:12,114 --> 00:45:16,139
That there is something which can see what's on the screen of consciousness.

567
00:45:16,860 --> 00:45:23,186
And that's what you're experiencing every time you see a pain in the knee and you say, there's a pain.

568
00:45:23,206 --> 00:45:27,050
The pain must be held somewhere for us to be able to acknowledge it, to see it.

569
00:45:27,871 --> 00:45:29,574
And there's something that acknowledges it.

570
00:45:31,275 --> 00:45:33,057
See, that's separation.

571
00:45:33,949 --> 00:45:37,574
So there you've got your avijapachya sankara.

572
00:45:37,594 --> 00:45:44,724
So dependent on these sankaras, this consciousness arises.

573
00:45:46,186 --> 00:45:48,889
And depending on consciousness, the body and mind.

574
00:45:49,230 --> 00:45:54,556
So here he's, as it were, taken consciousness out of those five bodies.

575
00:45:54,840 --> 00:46:21,000
aggregates that we talked about so nama rupa body mind he's taken it out and he's pointed out that these two things are like in you know in those days two sheaths of wheat leaning against each other again you can't have consciousness you can't have that ability of consciousness without the body mind complex and without consciousness you wouldn't know that there was a body mind complex

576
00:46:21,621 --> 00:46:23,264
So the two come together.

577
00:46:23,344 --> 00:46:26,548
But what he's saying here is that these are two different processes.

578
00:46:27,349 --> 00:46:27,849
That's the point.

579
00:46:28,351 --> 00:46:29,853
Constantly deconstructing.

580
00:46:31,454 --> 00:46:32,657
Constantly deconstructing.

581
00:46:35,340 --> 00:46:40,226
Now when it comes to the, where are we now?

582
00:46:40,246 --> 00:46:46,835
So now we've been through the five heaps, which is the consciousness and the body, heart, mind.

583
00:46:47,085 --> 00:46:53,454
The next step is to see that actually the way we contact the world is through the six senses.

584
00:46:53,474 --> 00:46:54,976
And that's your next thing.

585
00:46:54,996 --> 00:47:00,585
Dependent on this body-mind complex, the six sense bases arise.

586
00:47:00,644 --> 00:47:02,927
So that's the five that we obviously know.

587
00:47:03,469 --> 00:47:10,960
And the other one is where the brain and mind contact to create the inner percepts and then eventually concepts.

588
00:47:12,402 --> 00:47:12,722
See?

589
00:47:13,478 --> 00:47:22,309
So that's the point where the ability to contact the world out there and the world in here arises at the six sense bases.

590
00:47:22,668 --> 00:47:26,934
So when an image comes, it's on the sixth sense base.

591
00:47:26,954 --> 00:47:33,322
When an emotion comes in the mind, it's on the sixth sense base.

592
00:47:33,342 --> 00:47:37,527
And then dependent on the salayatana, we have this pasa, we have this contact.

593
00:47:39,449 --> 00:47:42,411
Now, contact is the moment where we experience something.

594
00:47:42,492 --> 00:47:43,373
What has to be there?

595
00:47:44,034 --> 00:47:45,094
There has to be a sense base.

596
00:47:45,894 --> 00:47:47,896
There has to be some sense base.

597
00:47:47,916 --> 00:47:49,059
Either the five or the mind.

598
00:47:49,978 --> 00:47:51,141
Emotions, thoughts, okay?

599
00:47:51,601 --> 00:47:53,902
There has to be an object which is being sensed.

600
00:47:54,643 --> 00:47:56,025
And there has to be this consciousness.

601
00:47:57,025 --> 00:47:58,288
That's the moment of contact.

602
00:47:59,329 --> 00:48:08,797
Now, when I describe to you what to do with pain in the knee, and your first noting is pain, pain, and all that sort of stuff, and aversion, aversion,

603
00:48:08,947 --> 00:48:11,690
And then you get that equanimity with it.

604
00:48:11,710 --> 00:48:13,472
I say go into the pain.

605
00:48:14,173 --> 00:48:17,117
And that's when you go beyond the concept of pain.

606
00:48:17,918 --> 00:48:21,204
Into where the mind and the body meet.

607
00:48:21,885 --> 00:48:24,648
And that's when you're noting changes to things like heat.

608
00:48:25,630 --> 00:48:26,090
Pressure.

609
00:48:27,592 --> 00:48:28,134
Stinging.

610
00:48:28,233 --> 00:48:29,014
All that sort of stuff.

611
00:48:29,114 --> 00:48:32,739
Which is the four great elements that we talked about.

612
00:48:33,561 --> 00:48:35,143
The fire, earth, water and air.

613
00:48:35,463 --> 00:48:37,907
Which stand for pressure.

614
00:48:38,242 --> 00:48:59,472
pressure temperature elasticity cohesion and movement so you're right there at the point of contact when you get down there you can't go beyond that that's it and it's upon those sensations that we're building the world see now dependent on

615
00:49:01,056 --> 00:49:04,601
dependent on Pasa, Vedana arises.

616
00:49:04,621 --> 00:49:05,483
So what's Vedana?

617
00:49:06,045 --> 00:49:07,867
Vedana is the five feelings.

618
00:49:07,947 --> 00:49:19,605
The five feelings of painful, pleasant, painful and pleasant physical feelings, and painful and pleasant mental feelings, which we would call emotions.

619
00:49:20,242 --> 00:49:21,184
And neutral.

620
00:49:21,364 --> 00:49:24,588
Neutral feelings, both physical and mental.

621
00:49:25,168 --> 00:49:26,110
Now what's happened there?

622
00:49:26,610 --> 00:49:31,556
We have defined what we're experiencing as either pleasant or unpleasant.

623
00:49:32,777 --> 00:49:34,579
And that's when you get the concept of pain.

624
00:49:38,382 --> 00:49:38,463
See?

625
00:49:38,483 --> 00:49:41,706
Now the world lives, we have to live in that dual world.

626
00:49:41,726 --> 00:49:47,713
Because everything we experience will either decide it's pleasant or unpleasant.

627
00:49:47,733 --> 00:49:47,853
Right?

628
00:49:53,268 --> 00:49:58,795
Now at that point, something happens.

629
00:49:59,958 --> 00:50:05,806
Something happens which is arising from this fundamental base of ignorance.

630
00:50:07,047 --> 00:50:11,393
Now, that not knowing, it's produced a delusion.

631
00:50:11,793 --> 00:50:13,657
What is the delusion?

632
00:50:13,717 --> 00:50:17,882
The delusion is, I am a human being.

633
00:50:19,706 --> 00:50:20,726
What a terrible delusion.

634
00:50:21,652 --> 00:50:22,893
I am a human being.

635
00:50:24,894 --> 00:50:30,221
And therefore, we are seeking happiness in the form of a human being.

636
00:50:32,123 --> 00:50:40,751
Seeking happiness in the form of a human being manifests as acquisitiveness, because I want to feel safe.

637
00:50:42,313 --> 00:50:43,733
Greed, acquisitiveness.

638
00:50:43,753 --> 00:50:46,376
The more I have, the safer I feel.

639
00:50:48,213 --> 00:50:50,014
It manifests as aversion.

640
00:50:50,215 --> 00:50:54,400
Anything that threatens what I have, I want to push away and destroy.

641
00:50:55,101 --> 00:50:55,461
Murder.

642
00:50:57,003 --> 00:50:59,306
And if it's too big, I run for it.

643
00:51:00,289 --> 00:51:02,351
At worst, suicide.

644
00:51:02,931 --> 00:51:07,838
So there's my relationship to the world from the position of delusion.

645
00:51:08,599 --> 00:51:11,262
The delusion is, I am this human being.

646
00:51:11,983 --> 00:51:13,146
I want to be happy.

647
00:51:14,306 --> 00:51:15,829
This is what makes me happy.

648
00:51:16,829 --> 00:51:18,152
And I collect all the money.

649
00:51:18,418 --> 00:51:22,003
all the friends, all the whatever.

650
00:51:22,864 --> 00:51:28,231
And anybody who takes anything from that is my enemy, is my rival, and must be destroyed.

651
00:51:29,353 --> 00:51:31,817
And if the rival and the enemy is too big, I've got to run.

652
00:51:33,059 --> 00:51:44,494
So those are my attitudes that are arising from this delusion of thinking, believing, identifying with this psychophysical organism.

653
00:51:45,925 --> 00:52:15,644
that fundamental delusion is running underneath every moment we live okay and when something comes into consciousness which we perceive as pleasant we'll immediately go up and grab it and try to hold on to it and try to develop it and if in consciousness something unpleasant comes that arises from this delusion the desire to get rid of it to destroy it or to run for it

654
00:52:16,164 --> 00:52:18,347
That's the point of tanha.

655
00:52:19,090 --> 00:52:28,885
That's what we're doing every time we fall into the error of, it's translated as craving, but you can see that word doesn't capture the meaning of it.

656
00:52:29,947 --> 00:52:34,112
It's the desire, it's the greed, it's the hatred, it's the aversion, etc.

657
00:52:34,853 --> 00:52:41,565
And the anxiety, that's coming from the pressure of not being able to handle a situation.

658
00:52:43,434 --> 00:52:44,615
And that's when it arises.

659
00:52:44,815 --> 00:52:47,119
So everything up to now has been a given.

660
00:52:47,318 --> 00:52:49,641
Even the Buddha experiences that.

661
00:52:49,661 --> 00:52:51,724
He experiences sensations coming in.

662
00:52:51,744 --> 00:52:54,106
He experiences them as pleasant or unpleasant.

663
00:52:55,047 --> 00:52:56,327
He experiences emotions.

664
00:52:57,168 --> 00:53:01,514
He experiences the four great Brahma Viharas.

665
00:53:01,574 --> 00:53:04,737
Love, compassion, joy and peacefulness.

666
00:53:05,257 --> 00:53:09,141
He's not a sort of amorphous blob or something.

667
00:53:09,722 --> 00:53:13,206
A callous and cold heart and pure wisdom

668
00:53:13,489 --> 00:53:19,378
I mean, it's like the wisdom and compassion arises naturally, is it?

669
00:53:20,719 --> 00:53:21,501
He's huggy-wuggy.

670
00:53:24,284 --> 00:53:25,206
Out of compassion.

671
00:53:25,467 --> 00:53:29,112
Whatever a teacher can do out of compassion for his students, I have done for you.

672
00:53:29,592 --> 00:53:31,396
He doesn't say out of wisdom, he says out of compassion.

673
00:53:33,177 --> 00:53:37,123
So up until then, it's natural to all human beings.

674
00:53:37,563 --> 00:53:37,945
But...

675
00:53:38,514 --> 00:53:46,443
From an enlightened point of view, there's not this other relationship because that fundamental delusion about who we are has disappeared.

676
00:53:48,126 --> 00:53:58,358
Now, every time we make in our meditation an object of what we are experiencing, we're undermining that delusion of a self.

677
00:53:58,958 --> 00:54:01,922
Because this self is saying, I am this body.

678
00:54:02,302 --> 00:54:04,083
So when you get a pain in the knee and you say,

679
00:54:04,317 --> 00:54:10,885
there's pain, you're undermining that delusion that I am this knee, or this knee is mine.

680
00:54:12,668 --> 00:54:28,570
Every time you have an emotion, anxiety, depression, every time you push it away inside, creating an outer world of the inner world, and you say there's depression, you're undermining this fundamental delusion about who you are.

681
00:54:29,916 --> 00:54:31,159
And that's the release.

682
00:54:31,219 --> 00:54:33,442
That's the process of liberation.

683
00:54:33,521 --> 00:54:34,603
That's the process of awakening.

684
00:54:36,485 --> 00:54:37,266
Same with thoughts.

685
00:54:38,148 --> 00:54:40,070
Thoughts are a bit quick, but definitely with images.

686
00:54:40,110 --> 00:54:42,273
You can hold an image and say, well, there's an image.

687
00:54:43,373 --> 00:54:48,400
And in that way, that objectification of the inner world is the process of liberation.

688
00:54:48,740 --> 00:54:52,545
But, whenever we fall into this tanha, we've lost it.

689
00:54:52,865 --> 00:54:54,007
We're back into the delusion.

690
00:54:55,929 --> 00:54:58,032
Now, that's the point of

691
00:54:58,317 --> 00:55:16,021
desire and that's what we're doing all the time in terms of noting intentions right some intentions of course are powered not by ignorance but by wisdom so they're obviously wants to be developed but when it's coming from this this center of a self right

692
00:55:16,356 --> 00:55:18,679
Then, of course, you have to be careful.

693
00:55:18,719 --> 00:55:22,003
Then it becomes something which is negative, undermining.

694
00:55:22,204 --> 00:55:25,427
But, at that point, remember, nothing's happened.

695
00:55:25,447 --> 00:55:28,871
That's what we're trying to really grasp by noting intentions.

696
00:55:29,952 --> 00:55:33,056
Nothing happens at the point of intention.

697
00:55:33,076 --> 00:55:39,443
Now, the next step, as you'll see, is... What is it?

698
00:55:39,543 --> 00:55:41,605
Where am I?

699
00:55:41,625 --> 00:55:44,068
Oh, dear me.

700
00:55:44,858 --> 00:55:45,518
Upadana.

701
00:55:45,679 --> 00:55:50,463
Upadana is the actual holding of the grasping.

702
00:55:51,103 --> 00:55:53,865
And that's the point where you say, this is me.

703
00:55:55,347 --> 00:55:57,809
That's the identification.

704
00:55:57,829 --> 00:56:02,835
Now, you can catch it in your meditation.

705
00:56:03,474 --> 00:56:09,501
You can be there, say, holding that pain separate.

706
00:56:10,362 --> 00:56:11,963
And you're noting pain, pain, pain.

707
00:56:12,246 --> 00:56:15,550
And then it just gets a bit too much.

708
00:56:16,032 --> 00:56:18,474
And then you say, I can't stand it.

709
00:56:18,855 --> 00:56:22,219
At that point, you see, the identification's gone in.

710
00:56:22,699 --> 00:56:23,981
And that's the point of suffering.

711
00:56:25,722 --> 00:56:32,431
So long as you can hold in your attention pleasant, unpleasant feelings as objects, you're not suffering.

712
00:56:33,132 --> 00:56:34,753
Make sure you can clearly see that.

713
00:56:35,594 --> 00:56:41,561
The separation of the consciousness, of that awareness from what it's being aware of,

714
00:56:42,182 --> 00:56:44,967
should be clearly acknowledged.

715
00:56:45,527 --> 00:56:49,813
There's pain, fine, but there's not suffering.

716
00:56:49,833 --> 00:56:52,135
Then this aversion comes.

717
00:56:52,195 --> 00:56:52,916
I don't want it.

718
00:56:52,956 --> 00:56:53,717
I don't want it.

719
00:56:54,438 --> 00:56:59,143
Making that your object, making it very clear, you're still not actually suffering.

720
00:56:59,465 --> 00:57:02,509
It's not a pleasant place, but you're not suffering.

721
00:57:02,528 --> 00:57:05,371
And as soon as you say, I can't take it, that's it.

722
00:57:05,793 --> 00:57:07,315
You're in there, and you're suffering.

723
00:57:08,315 --> 00:57:08,817
See?

724
00:57:08,836 --> 00:57:09,878
So the point of

725
00:57:10,498 --> 00:57:18,248
Suffering, as the Buddha points out, as opposed to pain, is at the point of identification.

726
00:57:18,268 --> 00:57:22,132
Now, the next step is the bit where the horror begins.

727
00:57:23,994 --> 00:57:26,958
Because upadana pachya bhava.

728
00:57:26,978 --> 00:57:31,704
Now, bhava is the point where you act.

729
00:57:31,724 --> 00:57:33,706
That's the point where the will goes in.

730
00:57:34,367 --> 00:57:38,231
And you create an act dependent on the delusion.

731
00:57:39,313 --> 00:57:39,713
Now,

732
00:57:40,132 --> 00:57:43,179
He uses the word bhava because bhava means becoming.

733
00:57:43,340 --> 00:57:44,123
What's becoming?

734
00:57:44,503 --> 00:57:47,773
The self is recreating itself all the time.

735
00:57:48,375 --> 00:57:49,639
The self isn't static.

736
00:57:49,719 --> 00:57:51,402
It feels static.

737
00:57:51,422 --> 00:57:55,574
You know, you wake up in the morning and you say, oh, it's me again.

738
00:57:56,702 --> 00:57:58,724
Or, oh, not me again.

739
00:57:59,925 --> 00:58:00,907
It's one or the other.

740
00:58:03,750 --> 00:58:08,494
So it's like you wake up and you suddenly realize, oh, it's me.

741
00:58:08,914 --> 00:58:09,876
You wake up to yourself.

742
00:58:09,916 --> 00:58:15,440
That me, that me, you see, is the essential delusion that's underlying all this.

743
00:58:16,322 --> 00:58:25,911
And as it comes up and identifies, it empowers that intention.

744
00:58:25,931 --> 00:58:26,592
And so

745
00:58:26,960 --> 00:58:29,804
The bhava is referring to a few things.

746
00:58:29,824 --> 00:58:35,936
It's referring, A, to this self reproducing itself as the one who's doing the action.

747
00:58:36,777 --> 00:58:44,289
It refers to the act of will that has gone into that process to take it from an intention into an action.

748
00:58:45,512 --> 00:58:47,735
And it's produced an act.

749
00:58:49,724 --> 00:58:50,003
See?

750
00:58:50,244 --> 00:59:04,443
And that's the next bit where he says, So, from that point of becoming, that's the point of the birth of your action.

751
00:59:05,744 --> 00:59:09,429
And from the birth of your action, you complete the action and it comes to the end.

752
00:59:09,730 --> 00:59:15,056
So that birth and death refer to the process of the action that you've determined.

753
00:59:17,246 --> 00:59:41,786
and you can't stop the consequence once you've put that out into the universe and into the inner universe you can't stop what's going to happen you can ameliorate it, you can mitigate its effects but you can't actually stop that energy from flowing outwards and inwards so for instance if you're sharp with somebody

754
00:59:41,969 --> 00:59:43,431
you can't stop the effect of that.

755
00:59:43,471 --> 00:59:46,715
You might have lost a friend forever, even though you might apologise.

756
00:59:47,217 --> 00:59:51,282
Inwardly, you've developed more of that sort of nastiness.

757
00:59:55,429 --> 00:59:59,755
So, that's a run-through, dependent origination.

758
01:00:03,340 --> 01:00:11,773
The underlying ignorance about who we are, creating certain attitudes, the acquisition, the aversion, the fear,

759
01:00:12,277 --> 01:00:17,844
and how it manifests in a process, which is completely opposite to our language.

760
01:00:18,286 --> 01:00:24,934
So, I want, and I scream, and I buy it.

761
01:00:25,936 --> 01:00:33,967
But the psychological process is, I scream, want, I buy.

762
01:00:35,530 --> 01:00:40,157
Now, if the I was first, there'd be no escape, would there?

763
01:00:43,106 --> 01:00:49,052
If the identity came first, you'd never be able to break through the process of desiring.

764
01:00:49,932 --> 01:00:58,661
It's the very fact that it comes after the process and therefore you can see the process of desiring that you can break the chain.

765
01:01:00,561 --> 01:01:05,567
You can see how amazingly deep the Buddha's insight was into our psychology.

766
01:01:07,608 --> 01:01:12,172
He saw exactly where the problem was.

767
01:01:12,192 --> 01:01:12,793
And

768
01:01:13,010 --> 01:01:14,931
It's like anything...

769
01:01:15,052 --> 01:01:19,074
When somebody climbs Everest... Like it's done...

770
01:01:19,094 --> 01:01:28,623
It's possible... Up until then it's not possible... And then somebody climbs Everest... And every man and his dog can get up there... You see what I mean?

771
01:01:28,643 --> 01:01:32,347
It's like he's opened the gates of the dark...

772
01:01:32,367 --> 01:01:36,110
So that's dependent origination... Now... On the way back...

773
01:01:36,130 --> 01:01:41,835
Whenever you stop... That process of wrong desire... Unwholesome desire...

774
01:01:42,322 --> 01:01:44,585
The end of that process doesn't happen.

775
01:01:44,804 --> 01:01:49,030
It just fizzles out right there at tanha, at desire.

776
01:01:52,096 --> 01:01:53,056
And that's the cure.

777
01:01:53,677 --> 01:02:01,708
That's the emptying of those sankara, those conditionings which are running underneath every day of our lives.

778
01:02:02,610 --> 01:02:04,353
And underneath that is the ignorance.

779
01:02:05,514 --> 01:02:12,244
So you've got this underlying energy of the not knowing, the essential delusions

780
01:02:12,746 --> 01:02:33,110
and all the habits that we've created by it, just running underneath every moment, every moment there's some stimulus, a greed, something that we greed for, or hate, or afraid of, and it comes into our consciousness, and something from below rises up to grasp it.

781
01:02:34,452 --> 01:02:39,699
If we can catch that rising, it'll just go and then plop, and that's the end of it.

782
01:02:40,239 --> 01:02:41,420
It just disappears.

783
01:02:41,688 --> 01:02:47,976
And that way we empty these sankara, that way we undermine this fundamental delusion.

784
01:02:48,996 --> 01:02:52,983
That's the point of escape between tanha and vedana.

785
01:02:53,182 --> 01:02:54,304
Vedana and tanha.

786
01:02:55,184 --> 01:02:56,327
That's the point of escape.

787
01:02:58,409 --> 01:03:05,858
And every time we're pushing something away to make it an object, we're actually cutting deep down into that sense of self.

788
01:03:07,221 --> 01:03:09,483
And there will come a time, be assured,

789
01:03:10,054 --> 01:03:15,123
when that sense of self is completely cut and the whole house of cards completely tumbles.

790
01:03:16,045 --> 01:03:21,213
And that's the point of total liberation.

791
01:03:21,233 --> 01:03:22,516
Maybe by Saturday noon.

792
01:03:25,601 --> 01:03:26,342
We'll have a bit of luck.

793
01:03:28,751 --> 01:03:33,038
So that's the process that he's pointing out when he goes backwards on it.

794
01:03:33,217 --> 01:03:36,081
It's not so much backwards, it's more like the negative qualities.

795
01:03:36,563 --> 01:03:42,110
Undermining that avijja, undermining that wrong understanding, the whole thing starts to collapse.

796
01:03:44,672 --> 01:03:53,726
And do remember that often because of the way he would explain things, it came out quite negatively.

797
01:03:54,407 --> 01:03:56,969
And so he was accused of annihilationism.

798
01:03:57,152 --> 01:04:00,300
So there's the not born, the not dying, the unconditioned.

799
01:04:00,340 --> 01:04:03,809
We say some of these things in one of our pujas.

800
01:04:05,313 --> 01:04:08,681
But he said, no, he said the only thing that's annihilated is this.

801
01:04:09,117 --> 01:04:12,342
is this acquisitiveness, aversion and fear.

802
01:04:12,362 --> 01:04:14,565
Everything else is given back, renewed.

803
01:04:15,005 --> 01:04:23,777
So remember, once he was fully liberated, there immediately arose within him that desire to help other people.

804
01:04:24,518 --> 01:04:29,286
It's not possible for wisdom to arise without that connection, the connection with other people.

805
01:04:29,907 --> 01:04:34,873
And as he is teaching, his teaching grows.

806
01:04:35,554 --> 01:04:45,110
There are early parts of the scriptures, some of you might know the Nipata Sutta, where he's sort of getting his thoughts together, because it's conversations with people.

807
01:04:45,130 --> 01:04:47,293
Then the middle part, it's all been formalized.

808
01:04:47,393 --> 01:04:49,516
Four of these, ten of those, twelve of them.

809
01:04:50,036 --> 01:04:52,460
He goes on like a list upon lists.

810
01:04:53,402 --> 01:04:56,606
And it's like he has to learn how to teach.

811
01:04:57,277 --> 01:05:10,815
I think I mentioned it on Saturday, where he rises from his seat with the idea of offering people this teaching, and he meets an ascetic on the road who says that, you know, you really look brilliant, you look absolutely shining.

812
01:05:10,835 --> 01:05:11,797
He says, who's your teacher?

813
01:05:12,237 --> 01:05:16,884
And he makes this amazing declaration, I need no teacher, I am the fully liberated one, and all that, you see.

814
01:05:17,284 --> 01:05:19,527
And the fellow says, very good, and walks off.

815
01:05:19,547 --> 01:05:20,248
LAUGHTER

816
01:05:20,228 --> 01:05:22,932
Which you would do, wouldn't you?

817
01:05:22,952 --> 01:05:26,418
Somebody stood here and said, I am the great guru, I am the cosmic Buddha.

818
01:05:30,284 --> 01:05:33,811
So I think he learned that you don't quite approach the process that way.

819
01:05:38,378 --> 01:05:43,628
So, the last thing I want to add to it is karma.

820
01:05:43,748 --> 01:05:44,329
Karma.

821
01:05:45,152 --> 01:05:51,925
By the way, I've done the we depend origination as a moment to moment process.

822
01:05:52,346 --> 01:05:57,135
Remember that there's also the teaching that this refers also to lifetimes.

823
01:05:57,155 --> 01:06:03,246
So that when we come into this life, we bring with us our past delusion and bad habits.

824
01:06:03,664 --> 01:06:08,751
our potentialities, and depending on the situation we're in, they'll be somehow developed.

825
01:06:09,351 --> 01:06:32,135
So we know this from children, that early childhood, often a child will react to things which are completely innocuous, but because of the delusion or unresolved feelings in them, they'll see it in a certain way, and it becomes possibly a trauma.

826
01:06:32,284 --> 01:06:38,021
And then, you know, this business of false memory syndrome, you know, where you get false memory and all that.

827
01:06:38,041 --> 01:06:40,668
Well, just to reinforce that, I had one myself.

828
01:06:41,269 --> 01:06:46,664
Because in the early part of my meditation, when I was practicing Zen,

829
01:06:47,067 --> 01:06:52,896
I was just resting and I lay on the bed and this huge sort of fear came up.

830
01:06:52,916 --> 01:06:55,561
Every cell of my body was electric with this fear.

831
01:06:56,061 --> 01:07:00,670
And a very clear image that I walked into the room to my grandfather.

832
01:07:00,710 --> 01:07:05,237
And I mustn't have been more than two years old because he died shortly after that.

833
01:07:05,838 --> 01:07:10,447
And I shook him and I said to myself, he's dead, they've killed him.

834
01:07:11,188 --> 01:07:12,771
They happen to be my parents.

835
01:07:15,501 --> 01:07:22,791
I went to my father, luckily he was still alive, and I said to him, Dad, I found grandfather dead in the front room.

836
01:07:23,612 --> 01:07:25,172
He says, no, he died in bed, I was with him.

837
01:07:26,996 --> 01:07:33,143
Now, if he wasn't there, I'd go around telling everybody, you know, I had this terrible trauma, caught my grandfather dead in the chair.

838
01:07:33,844 --> 01:07:41,072
Now, the point is, it's true, in the sense of that's how I interpreted what I saw, but it wasn't true historically.

839
01:07:42,353 --> 01:07:42,454
Yeah.

840
01:07:42,755 --> 01:07:59,500
Now, the interesting thing about that particular experience was that when it came up, I had a backflow, a forward flow of all my relationships to show me how that particular trauma had cancered every relationship.

841
01:08:01,342 --> 01:08:03,405
And from that moment on, my relationships changed.

842
01:08:05,088 --> 01:08:07,632
That's how deep our delusion can lie.

843
01:08:08,333 --> 01:08:08,592
You see?

844
01:08:09,755 --> 01:08:11,998
Not everybody has these things, by the way.

845
01:08:13,679 --> 01:08:15,762
It's not necessary to have a trauma.

846
01:08:18,447 --> 01:08:23,774
So that for me was a great teaching about karma, you see.

847
01:08:24,295 --> 01:08:28,319
So somehow, I mean, I'm

848
01:08:28,925 --> 01:08:36,135
I put credence in the whole idea of past lives, but even if you don't, just the idea of a young child who is feeling vulnerable.

849
01:08:36,414 --> 01:08:37,777
So you know children react.

850
01:08:38,096 --> 01:08:41,942
They think that if the parents are arguing, they're the problem, etc., etc.

851
01:08:42,443 --> 01:08:51,515
So whatever that decision was, remember the child is filled with that complete delusion that I am the body.

852
01:08:53,117 --> 01:08:55,020
And so that remains in the system.

853
01:08:55,520 --> 01:08:57,462
And you can see the karmic flow of it, you see.

854
01:08:59,654 --> 01:09:06,682
So karma, in terms of, I'm using karma in the more common sense of, you know, your comeuppance.

855
01:09:08,024 --> 01:09:16,435
Karma is to do with your inner world.

856
01:09:16,534 --> 01:09:20,099
It's not to do with your outer world when it comes to the process of liberation.

857
01:09:21,581 --> 01:09:27,307
And when something happens to us, there can be a multitude of reasons for it.

858
01:09:27,328 --> 01:09:29,390
In Buddhist understanding, there are five laws.

859
01:09:29,707 --> 01:09:55,614
most of it well they all equate to our own modern laws the first one is known as the law of heat or energy that's all the physical laws so these poor people in nepal i mean they've had another terrible earthquake up there that's not because in their past lives they crushed a hundred thousand ants to death you know i mean it just happens because you happen to be on the earth so you can't say that an earthquake or a flooding is your personal karma it's ridiculous

860
01:09:56,067 --> 01:09:58,451
So it's the same with bija, the seeds.

861
01:09:58,631 --> 01:09:59,631
That's our genetics.

862
01:09:59,972 --> 01:10:04,179
You can't say the body, you know, you deserve the body you've got.

863
01:10:04,198 --> 01:10:07,543
It's a given through that whole genetic line.

864
01:10:08,045 --> 01:10:09,747
So that's not your personal karma.

865
01:10:09,766 --> 01:10:12,912
It's not the karma that you're looking at when you want to be liberated.

866
01:10:14,274 --> 01:10:19,582
Then there's the whole law of psychology, the citta, right?

867
01:10:19,622 --> 01:10:24,028
The whole psychology, which includes our perceptual process, etc., etc.

868
01:10:24,448 --> 01:10:29,055
And a lot of that is dependent upon the brain that you were given.

869
01:10:30,055 --> 01:10:38,487
And then number four is karma, which is to do just that point of willing things and creating habits.

870
01:10:38,908 --> 01:10:39,708
There's your karma.

871
01:10:40,110 --> 01:10:45,557
And it's that karma that will make you do things which then reverberate back on you.

872
01:10:47,260 --> 01:10:52,966
You know, like just getting angry with somebody then you find they're getting angry with you for heaven's sake.

873
01:10:53,127 --> 01:11:00,296
So it's that sort of understanding that it's really only around ethics that we have personal karma.

874
01:11:00,815 --> 01:11:07,645
And go back to the original experience of the Buddha there upon enlightenment those three knowledges that we talk about.

875
01:11:07,765 --> 01:11:08,886
The knowledge that he is

876
01:11:09,203 --> 01:11:15,591
has no more defilements in him, that he sees all his past lives driven by his ethical decisions.

877
01:11:16,072 --> 01:11:21,819
And he sees beings being born from one realm to another also driven by their ethical decisions.

878
01:11:22,341 --> 01:11:25,805
So it's ethics, right?

879
01:11:25,824 --> 01:11:31,091
And then finally, of course, there are the spiritual laws, which include the Four Noble Truths, etc., etc.

880
01:11:32,033 --> 01:11:36,139
So karma, dependence origination and karma,

881
01:11:36,895 --> 01:12:01,569
are to be seen as one and the same thing he's actually describing how we create karma for ourselves and how we can overcome it okay I can only hope my words have been of some assistance and it has not brought more confusion

882
01:12:02,326 --> 01:12:13,381
And that by your careful investigation, discrimination of all your experiences, you may finally reach that pure liberation from all suffering, sooner rather than later.

